scrolly-map.Copy: Before the invasion, Russian or Russian-supported forces controlled Crimea and parts of Donetsk and Luhansk.
Two weeks into the war, Russian forces were just a handful of miles from the capital, Kyiv.
But a month later, this threat was reduced. Ukraine carried out its first successful counteroffensive in the north of the country, and Russian forces were pushed away from Kyiv.
Further counterattacks pushed the Russians away from the northern city of Kharkiv in September.

In November, Ukrainian forces regained the capital of the illegally annexed Kherson region. While much of the region's land remains in Russian hands, this was the only regional capital that Russia had seized.
Now, one year on, the two sides are locked in stalemate. Russian forces have once again made a few gains in Donetsk, with fighting centred on Bakhmut, but these have come at a high cost.

scrolly-chart.Header: Russia retreats from Kyiv in April
scrolly-chart.Copy: After an initial rush on the Ukrainian capital failed, Russian forces retreated from the north.
Russia's focus on the east slowly worked, with territorial advances in Luhansk and Donetsk.
Throughout most of summer 2022, an uneasy stalemate ensued, with neither side able to break through.
This changed in early September, when Ukrainian forces liberated the vast majority of Kharkiv region.
Ukraine won another key victory in Kherson. While Russia still controlled most of the region's land, the capital city was home to more than a quarter of the region's prewar population.

scrolly-chart.Header: Winter stalemate and heavy Donetsk fighting
scrolly-chart.Copy: The frontlines remain static, with the exception of some Russian gains in Donetsk that have come at high cost to both sides.
